e shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Skelton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Yorkshire): habitational name mainly from Skelton in Cumberland, or any of various places called Skelton in Yorkshire, North Yorkshire, and East Yorkshire. The placenames probably all derive from Old English <i>scelf</i> ‘rock, ledge, shelf’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’, with initial <i>Sk-</i>, instead of <i>Sh-</i>, due to Scandinavian influence. However, in some cases, the first element may be a lost river name, from Old Norse <i>skjallr</i> ‘resounding’; compare   Skelding  . This English surname has been established in Queen's County [Laois], Ireland, since the 16th century."],"variants":[{"name":"Skelding","meanings":["English: habitational name from Skelding (Yorkshire). The place takes its name from the river Skell, itself from Old Norse <i>skjallr</i> ‘resounding’, + Old English <i>denu</i> ‘valley’. In addition, the name may come from Skeldon (Ayrshire), although there is a lack of evidence for a historic presence in this part of Scotland."]},{"name":"Skilton","meanings":["English (Surrey): probably a variant of   Skelton  , though in some cases the name may be a variant of <b>Shilton</b>, a habitational name from Shilton (Warwickshire, Oxfordshire) or Earl Shilton (Leicestershire), from Old English <i>scelf</i>, <i>scylf</i> ‘rock, ledge, shelf’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","meanings":["Greek: the Lord gave graciously; whom Jehovah gave; whom Jehovah bestowed."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs. John de Skelton was born in 1281, in Armathwaite, Cumberland, England, United Kingdom. She had at least 5 sons with John de Skelton. She died about 1352, in her hometown, at the age of 72."},"et":{"1281–about 1352":"1281–umbes 1352","1278–1342":"1278–1342","1310–1342":"1310–1342","1312–Male":"1312–Surnud","1317–Male":"1317–Surnud","1331–1365":"1331–1365","1